2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>",{"id":243,"html":244},"commentary","\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>In detailed study of the theatre in 1986 this was the only inscription identified on the preserved seats. It is a reasonable assumption that since the same pair of letters is repeated, they have the same reference. The text on the vertical face of the seat (text B) is presented in the form of a monogram, with alpha much smaller and placed within the pi. The implication of the larger letters set out on the horizontal surface (text A) is that the small alpha should be read first in resolving such a monogrammatic presentation.\u003C/p>  ",{"id":246,"html":247},"bibliography","\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> Isler 1986 29-30 with fig. 3 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001915\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001915\u003C/a>  \u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>  \u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  ",{"id":249,"html":250},"handnote"," \u003Cp>Large plain letters without serifs on the flat surface, smaller but similar on the vertical face; alpha is broad with a straight bar; pi has verticals of equal length and there is no extension of the horizontal beyond the verticals.\u003C/p> \u003Cp> Types list: \u003Ca href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Α-type1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Α type1\u003C/a> \u003Ca href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Α-type1.3.html\" target=\"_blank\">Α type1.3\u003C/a> \u003Ca href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Π-type1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Π type1\u003C/a> \u003Ca href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Π-type1.1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Π type1.1\u003C/a> \u003Ca href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Π-type2.html\" target=\"_blank\">Π t